And then, you go
to [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:51.990 --> 00:39:53.330
ROBERT REID: Yeah, it's funny.

00:39:53.330 --> 00:39:57.630
There was, years ago, in Vietnam
in Hue, there was a

00:39:57.630 --> 00:39:58.620
place that's still there--

00:39:58.620 --> 00:39:59.230
I presume.

00:39:59.230 --> 00:40:00.940
It was a few years ago--

00:40:00.940 --> 00:40:04.360
that's a noodle place that was
run by a deaf-mute family.

00:40:04.360 --> 00:40:05.910
And Lonely Planet
wrote about it.

00:40:05.910 --> 00:40:07.930
And of course, you're going to
go to the deaf-mute place.

00:40:07.930 --> 00:40:09.340
Of course, everyone's
going to go there.

00:40:09.340 --> 00:40:11.180
So some of this is
classic Vietnam.

00:40:11.180 --> 00:40:14.330
So they created a place next
door, some other people, and

00:40:14.330 --> 00:40:17.650
named it the same thing and
pretended to be deaf and mute.

00:40:17.650 --> 00:40:20.460
I love Vietnam.

00:40:20.460 --> 00:40:21.170
OK.

00:40:21.170 --> 00:40:23.940
That's great.

00:40:23.940 --> 00:40:25.970
I think that it's up
to the traveler.

00:40:25.970 --> 00:40:27.600
I'm sorry when I see that.

00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:31.640
It's like that's the problem,
when you talk about the

00:40:31.640 --> 00:40:34.660
Khaosan Road in Bangkok is a
perfect example about just

00:40:34.660 --> 00:40:37.220
completely lines a tourist
ghetto, essentially.

00:40:37.220 --> 00:40:39.860
And almost everyone
has Lonely Planet.

00:40:39.860 --> 00:40:45.410
And it's just how do you cover
that so that you don't have

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:47.800
one with a giant line?

00:40:47.800 --> 00:40:50.470
And I think that part of it is
tempering your enthusiasm for

00:40:50.470 --> 00:40:53.620
places that Lonely
Planet dominates.

00:40:53.620 --> 00:40:56.510
It's a very subtle thing, but
it's like sometimes it's

00:40:56.510 --> 00:41:00.950
better to say there's 15 guest
houses on this street.

00:41:00.950 --> 00:41:03.360
You can get rooms with air
conditioning and a silly

00:41:03.360 --> 00:41:06.490
little refrigerator you won't
need for about $12 for one

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:08.090
person, $15 for two.

00:41:08.090 --> 00:41:09.150
And you can go there.

00:41:09.150 --> 00:41:11.740
And here's a few examples if you
need a number, but there's

00:41:11.740 --> 00:41:14.410
a lot and the changeover's
very quick.

00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:15.850
They come and go frequently.

00:41:15.850 --> 00:41:16.970
You'll find something there.

00:41:16.970 --> 00:41:18.950
I think that sometimes I'd like
to see a little more of

00:41:18.950 --> 00:41:21.860
that in those cases, in those
cases in particular.

00:41:21.860 --> 00:41:24.690
If someone's going to pay $200
or pay more money, then you

00:41:24.690 --> 00:41:29.220
can stand to put a more solid
review for it, because people

00:41:29.220 --> 00:41:30.950
are really wanting to make
sure they have someplace

00:41:30.950 --> 00:41:33.190
that's very comfortable, that
they have all the amenities

00:41:33.190 --> 00:41:35.750
and thread counts that they
need, et cetera, which is

00:41:35.750 --> 00:41:36.390
important too.

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:38.300
But then you would write
more about it.

00:41:38.300 --> 00:41:41.330
This is in terms of
accommodation.

00:41:41.330 --> 00:41:43.530
So I like the idea when
you just point people

00:41:43.530 --> 00:41:44.940
to the right way.

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:48.640
And they're going to find the
same thing, but not all at the

00:41:48.640 --> 00:41:49.680
same place.

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:51.750
But it's ultimately
the traveler.

00:41:51.750 --> 00:41:53.530
As people travel more,
they get that.

00:41:53.530 --> 00:41:55.090
They learn that a little bit.

00:41:55.090 --> 00:41:57.700
Some of the first and second
time travelers that go to a

00:41:57.700 --> 00:42:00.280
place, they don't
quite know yet--

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:03.900
that they don't have maybe the
confidence, perhaps, to

00:42:03.900 --> 00:42:05.860
completely put the guidebook
down-- it got them to the

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:07.450
right area-- and go
figure it out.

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:09.200
But I think people get
there pretty quick.

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:10.680
I hope.

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:12.630
I don't know?

00:42:12.630 --> 00:42:14.680
Any other questions?

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:15.160
Thoughts?

00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:17.250
Complaints?

00:42:17.250 --> 00:42:17.760
Complaint?

00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:19.704
No, just checking.

00:42:19.704 --> 00:42:21.880
AUDIENCE: How much traveling
do you do just for you as

00:42:21.880 --> 00:42:24.422
opposed to writing an article
or researching or making a

00:42:24.422 --> 00:42:25.160
video or whatever?

00:42:25.160 --> 00:42:30.080
Do you ever not take notes
and write them up?

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:32.750
ROBERT REID: Well, there are
some trips that you do--

00:42:32.750 --> 00:42:34.980
that's the problem is knowing
how to turn it off.

00:42:34.980 --> 00:42:37.030
And when we do travel writing,
you feel like everything you

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:39.770
do, there's experiences
you can use somehow.

00:42:39.770 --> 00:42:42.550
I have a unique position that
a lot of times we're talking

00:42:42.550 --> 00:42:48.570
on radio or TV or something
about that, so I might have an

00:42:48.570 --> 00:42:50.560
experience in Ecuador
that I use that way.

00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:51.610
I'm not writing about it.

00:42:51.610 --> 00:42:53.850
It's just kind of in the
back of your mind.

00:42:53.850 --> 00:42:56.340
But I don't know
the answer yet.

00:42:56.340 --> 00:42:58.760
Because I work too
much sometimes.

00:42:58.760 --> 00:43:02.380
I try to write or make a
video about everything.

00:43:02.380 --> 00:43:05.580
So they get backed up, because
it takes a long time.

00:43:05.580 --> 00:43:06.590
It doesn't stop.

00:43:06.590 --> 00:43:10.300
I mean, that's a great thing
about this work is that travel

00:43:10.300 --> 00:43:12.550
doesn't ever stop.

00:43:12.550 --> 00:43:14.160
And I see the space
tourism stuff.

00:43:14.160 --> 00:43:14.960
I'm just going why are you--

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:16.160
[FRUSTRATED  GROAN].

00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:17.920
Nah, I'm not ready for that.

00:43:17.920 --> 00:43:21.000
I think there's enough
here to work with.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.340
But I don't have $190,000 or how
much ever ever it costs.

00:43:24.340 --> 00:43:28.946
But it's hard to stop it,
to be honest, work

00:43:28.946 --> 00:43:32.220
less, but I like that.

00:43:32.220 --> 00:43:32.850
Yes.

00:43:32.850 --> 00:43:36.150
AUDIENCE: Why are travel books
so very centered on finding

00:43:36.150 --> 00:43:38.580
accommodations, finding
restaurants, and having

00:43:38.580 --> 00:43:41.130
categories with bars,
cafes, and so on.

00:43:41.130 --> 00:43:42.960
It's so boring to read.

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:44.915
You can't pick up a Lonely
Planet and read

00:43:44.915 --> 00:43:46.190
it from front to--

00:43:46.190 --> 00:43:48.090
it's too boring.

00:43:48.090 --> 00:43:51.240
I'd like to have more
description of the

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:51.860
neighborhoods.

00:43:51.860 --> 00:43:55.550
That takes place in this
piece at the beginning.

00:43:55.550 --> 00:43:58.000
ROBERT REID: A lot of people
use them different ways.

00:43:58.000 --> 00:43:59.720
It is a reference book
on some level.

00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:05.280
I mean, to me, I know how to use
them in a way that I can

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:08.050
be inspired by it, even if I'm
not reading every page.

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:09.190
I'll read the opening.

00:44:09.190 --> 00:44:11.200
I mean you sit in a bookstore,
and you compare guidebooks.

00:44:11.200 --> 00:44:14.660
Read the opening paragraph to
several different cities.

00:44:14.660 --> 00:44:16.370
And if you're at the city,
what's within three hours?

00:44:16.370 --> 00:44:17.850
Go to the transportation--
you see three

00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:18.900
hours here, three here.

00:44:18.900 --> 00:44:20.360
Go and look at those places.

00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:21.920
And you can imagine building
your own itinerary.

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:23.980
And it has all the information
that you can figure out.

00:44:23.980 --> 00:44:26.660
Oh, I land here, then I can go
see this and this and this.

00:44:26.660 --> 00:44:29.950
You're not going to read it
front to back, you're right.

00:44:29.950 --> 00:44:31.530
It's just not designed
to do that.

00:44:31.530 --> 00:44:34.490
I would love to be able to see
more space about neighborhoods

00:44:34.490 --> 00:44:36.420
and a little bit more
asides and features

00:44:36.420 --> 00:44:37.040
and things like that.

00:44:37.040 --> 00:44:40.130
There are some.

00:44:40.130 --> 00:44:44.730
And as a writer, it isn't the
most rewarding writing.

00:44:44.730 --> 00:44:45.555
It's the power of inclusion.

00:44:45.555 --> 00:44:48.090
It's what you include and
where you place it.

00:44:48.090 --> 00:44:50.150
And how much you talk about that
guest house that has a

00:44:50.150 --> 00:44:54.920
line and everyone's going to,
versus that hidden beach and

00:44:54.920 --> 00:44:59.000
thinking about the science
of how you include stuff.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:44:59.970
I know what you mean.

00:44:59.970 --> 00:45:00.590
I know what you mean.

00:45:00.590 --> 00:45:05.620
But it's just used
as a reference.

00:45:05.620 --> 00:45:09.300
And then you get the little
areas where you can flash your

00:45:09.300 --> 00:45:13.830
style in the little box text
and things like that.

00:45:13.830 --> 00:45:17.420
City guides have more of that
than a multi-country guide.

00:45:17.420 --> 00:45:20.680
Eastern Europe is going to be
much more bare-bone and kind

00:45:20.680 --> 00:45:23.970
of reference then the Rio
city guide or the Paris

00:45:23.970 --> 00:45:25.260
city guide would be.

00:45:25.260 --> 00:45:27.220
They'll have more on the
neighborhoods in that.

00:45:27.220 --> 00:45:31.010
But, yeah, I'd love to
not stop writing.

00:45:31.010 --> 00:45:36.160
But they got word counts
to adhere to.

00:45:36.160 --> 00:45:36.840
Yes?

00:45:36.840 --> 00:45:39.000
AUDIENCE: Do you have any
bad food experiences?

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:39.520
ROBERT REID: I have.

00:45:39.520 --> 00:45:42.730
I've vomited on a lot of
different countries.

00:45:42.730 --> 00:45:45.610
I'll give you a vomit
list later.

00:45:45.610 --> 00:45:47.620
Yeah, the funny thing is a lot
of people think that there's

00:45:47.620 --> 00:45:50.440
street food and you see bugs
for sale and little street

00:45:50.440 --> 00:45:51.250
tacos and stuff.

00:45:51.250 --> 00:45:53.870
And generally speaking, those
can be very safe.

00:45:53.870 --> 00:45:57.540
I mean, if they're making it
fresh and its meats and stuff

00:45:57.540 --> 00:45:58.230
aren't sitting out.

00:45:58.230 --> 00:46:00.720
And they've been made, and the
sauce is getting under the sun

00:46:00.720 --> 00:46:02.620
and things like that, then
you could have problems.

00:46:02.620 --> 00:46:05.250
But generally little kind of mom
and pop places and stuff

00:46:05.250 --> 00:46:07.390
that are fresh, they have a high
turnover of food, you see

00:46:07.390 --> 00:46:10.170
a lot of people eating there,
those are almost always safer.

00:46:10.170 --> 00:46:12.780
I mean, the most sick I ever got
was in Vietnam eating at a

00:46:12.780 --> 00:46:16.810
very nice Thai restaurant,
sitting down, air conditioned,

00:46:16.810 --> 00:46:18.210
bamboo interiors,
and all this.

00:46:18.210 --> 00:46:19.410
I'm the only one there.

00:46:19.410 --> 00:46:21.990
And I get ridiculously sick
and vomit for days.

00:46:21.990 --> 00:46:26.440
And so it isn't about so
much the condition.

00:46:26.440 --> 00:46:27.420
In Vietnam--

00:46:27.420 --> 00:46:29.870
I lived in Vietnam, that's
why I mention it a lot--

00:46:29.870 --> 00:46:33.270
you go to places with
cockroaches and you're fine.

00:46:33.270 --> 00:46:36.160
A little kind of outside
sidewalk selling pho noodles,

00:46:36.160 --> 00:46:37.400
and it's totally fine.

00:46:37.400 --> 00:46:39.800
But it's just because you're
outside and sometimes there's

00:46:39.800 --> 00:46:41.880
cockroaches in Vietnam.

00:46:41.880 --> 00:46:42.920
That's fine.

00:46:42.920 --> 00:46:45.880
As long as they don't
get in the soup.

00:46:45.880 --> 00:46:48.790
But yeah, I have gotten sick.

00:46:48.790 --> 00:46:49.900
It happens.

00:46:49.900 --> 00:46:51.430
Dehydration is the
worst though.

00:46:51.430 --> 00:46:53.280
Because you forget
to drink water.

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:54.100
And you're moving around.

00:46:54.100 --> 00:46:55.610
We move so much more when
we're traveling.

00:46:55.610 --> 00:46:57.220
You're constantly
outside moving.

00:46:57.220 --> 00:46:58.920
We're in New York,
we walk some.

00:46:58.920 --> 00:47:00.460
A lot of people don't walk.

00:47:00.460 --> 00:47:02.590
And they go somewhere, and
then they don't realize

00:47:02.590 --> 00:47:04.960
they're out in the sun,
and oh my god.

00:47:04.960 --> 00:47:06.790
That's what happened to
me in Yakutsk, Russia.

00:47:06.790 --> 00:47:10.210
I got this unbelievable heat
exhaustion, heat stroke thing.

00:47:10.210 --> 00:47:14.650
I was completely out of it
for two or three days.

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:15.890
Sick.

00:47:15.890 --> 00:47:16.370
Crime?

00:47:16.370 --> 00:47:17.580
Should we talk about crime?

00:47:17.580 --> 00:47:18.270
No.

00:47:18.270 --> 00:47:20.630
I don't have to talk
about that then.

00:47:20.630 --> 00:47:23.810
Any other questions
about travel?

00:47:23.810 --> 00:47:24.260
Yes.

00:47:24.260 --> 00:47:26.680
AUDIENCE: What strategies have
you seen effective for people

00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:29.100
who want to do open-ended travel
but are like us, and

00:47:29.100 --> 00:47:32.490
have full-time desk jobs?

00:47:32.490 --> 00:47:32.810
ROBERT REID: Quitting.

00:47:32.810 --> 00:47:36.790
Yeah, quit your job.

00:47:36.790 --> 00:47:37.220
I don't know.

00:47:37.220 --> 00:47:38.630
I don't know how
it works here.

00:47:38.630 --> 00:47:41.120
I mean, you see there is a huge
trend of people taking

00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:42.010
career breaks.

00:47:42.010 --> 00:47:43.380
That's very normal in Europe.

00:47:43.380 --> 00:47:48.060
Here, this cursed land, people
work and work and work and

00:47:48.060 --> 00:47:48.815
have two weeks vacation.

00:47:48.815 --> 00:47:50.810
And so we talk about ugly
Americans, because they don't

00:47:50.810 --> 00:47:52.330
get to travel as much.

00:47:52.330 --> 00:47:54.150
And they stick around the
United States and stuff.

00:47:54.150 --> 00:47:55.130
We don't have as
much vacation.

00:47:55.130 --> 00:47:55.830
It is hard.

00:47:55.830 --> 00:47:56.810
It's a challenge.

00:47:56.810 --> 00:47:58.270
But there's a huge
trend of it.

00:47:58.270 --> 00:48:00.830
There's a lot of books and sites
that are talking about

00:48:00.830 --> 00:48:02.360
taking career breaks and
things like this.

00:48:02.360 --> 00:48:03.600
Does Google allow
a career break?

00:48:03.600 --> 00:48:04.980
Is this controversial?

00:48:04.980 --> 00:48:07.560
Are you allowed to
take months off?

00:48:07.560 --> 00:48:08.470
I think everyone
should do that.

00:48:08.470 --> 00:48:11.180
It's human.

00:48:11.180 --> 00:48:13.320
I don't know what to tell you.

00:48:13.320 --> 00:48:16.010
It depends on where you work
and what the program is.

00:48:16.010 --> 00:48:19.370
And maybe do something you can
work remotely, and you can set

00:48:19.370 --> 00:48:24.760
up in Nicaragua and surf the
waves and work from there for

00:48:24.760 --> 00:48:25.695
very, very cheap.

00:48:25.695 --> 00:48:26.850
Who knows?

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:29.280
I'm afraid I don't know.

00:48:29.280 --> 00:48:30.530
Or you could be a
travel writer.

00:48:34.440 --> 00:48:35.350
Any other questions?

00:48:35.350 --> 00:48:36.440
Anyone planning a trip?

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:37.310
Don't know where to go?

00:48:37.310 --> 00:48:39.234
We can figure out your
trip for you.

00:48:39.234 --> 00:48:40.222
Yes.

00:48:40.222 --> 00:48:42.444
AUDIENCE: Well, I'm trying to
decide for next year-- we have

00:48:42.444 --> 00:48:42.692
a honeymoon.

00:48:42.692 --> 00:48:44.915
[? Would it be ?] better
to go to Scandinavia or

00:48:44.915 --> 00:48:46.650
do maybe a UK tour.

00:48:46.650 --> 00:48:47.460
ROBERT REID: A UK tour?

00:48:47.460 --> 00:48:49.610
AUDIENCE: Not like a tour group
but just all around.

00:48:49.610 --> 00:48:50.420
ROBERT REID: Yeah.

00:48:50.420 --> 00:48:52.780
And when would the
honeymoon be?

00:48:52.780 --> 00:48:53.276
AUDIENCE: July.

00:48:53.276 --> 00:48:54.526
ROBERT REID: OK.

00:48:57.250 --> 00:48:59.350
Do you speak other language--
well, everyone speaks English

00:48:59.350 --> 00:49:01.240
in Scandinavia.

00:49:01.240 --> 00:49:02.610
Well, I don't know
what to say.

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:04.950
I mean, it depends
on what you want.

00:49:04.950 --> 00:49:07.430
I think England and Britain is
one of the most underrated

00:49:07.430 --> 00:49:10.010
destinations, because
it's so different.

00:49:10.010 --> 00:49:11.000
We live in New York.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.320
All of our namesakes here
in this country

00:49:13.320 --> 00:49:13.960
are linked to there.

00:49:13.960 --> 00:49:14.870
And you can talk to everyone.

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:15.970
And there's stories
on every street.

00:49:15.970 --> 00:49:16.610
I lived in London.

00:49:16.610 --> 00:49:17.630
I love it.

00:49:17.630 --> 00:49:18.900
I actually like it more
than New York.

00:49:18.900 --> 00:49:20.100
I don't say that often.

00:49:20.100 --> 00:49:21.220
But I do.

00:49:21.220 --> 00:49:24.350
And you could have
a fantastic time.

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:26.140
Oh but, oh my gosh,
you get the fjords

00:49:26.140 --> 00:49:26.800
and stuff like that.

00:49:26.800 --> 00:49:28.710
Great food in Scandinavia.

00:49:28.710 --> 00:49:29.580
Oh my god.

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:33.530
I had a great time
in Copenhagen.

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:35.610
Go way up, way all the way up.

00:49:35.610 --> 00:49:37.350
Just go to Norway
all the way up.

00:49:37.350 --> 00:49:38.460
It'd be hard to beat that.

00:49:38.460 --> 00:49:39.430
It's beautiful.

00:49:39.430 --> 00:49:40.650
I don't know what to tell you.

00:49:40.650 --> 00:49:41.140
I don't know.

00:49:41.140 --> 00:49:42.880
How would you get around?

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:45.520
You would get around by
train, a train pass,

00:49:45.520 --> 00:49:46.530
or you would drive?

00:49:46.530 --> 00:49:48.030
AUDIENCE: Probably
mostly train.

00:49:48.030 --> 00:49:49.650
[INAUDIBLE]

00:49:49.650 --> 00:49:51.280
ROBERT REID: I would be tempted
to do Norway and back

00:49:51.280 --> 00:49:52.170
down through Sweden.

00:49:52.170 --> 00:49:53.710
Go all the way up past
the Arctic Circle.

00:49:53.710 --> 00:49:55.450
You can get the train
pass and do that.

00:49:55.450 --> 00:49:56.940
Go to the fjords and
stuff like that.

00:49:56.940 --> 00:49:58.160
That'd be great.

00:49:58.160 --> 00:49:59.480
That'd be great.

00:49:59.480 --> 00:50:00.370
I haven't done that.

00:50:00.370 --> 00:50:02.040
So that's what I would do.

00:50:02.040 --> 00:50:03.651
If you need a third,
let me know.

00:50:06.420 --> 00:50:07.970
Any other questions?

00:50:07.970 --> 00:50:08.470
Yes.

00:50:08.470 --> 00:50:10.350
AUDIENCE: Do you travel
with a [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:10.350 --> 00:50:11.600
or do you [INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:14.040 --> 00:50:16.330
ROBERT REID: You mean
for my hair?

00:50:16.330 --> 00:50:18.510
No, you mean like someone there,
that's helping you

00:50:18.510 --> 00:50:19.830
research and stuff like that.

00:50:19.830 --> 00:50:22.750
No, I mean when you did
guidebooks, I would go often

00:50:22.750 --> 00:50:24.140
anonymously in places.

00:50:24.140 --> 00:50:25.770
And I always love when
they say well, Lonely

00:50:25.770 --> 00:50:27.550
Planet never came here.

00:50:27.550 --> 00:50:28.540
Yeah, actually we did.

00:50:28.540 --> 00:50:30.340
We just didn't tell you.

00:50:30.340 --> 00:50:33.790
So a lot of it was very,
very independent.

00:50:33.790 --> 00:50:36.710
I worked in Colombia
on the Columbia

00:50:36.710 --> 00:50:37.660
guide a few years ago.

00:50:37.660 --> 00:50:40.300
And my Spanish kind of
dipped sometimes.

00:50:40.300 --> 00:50:44.020
And so I got some people to go
around, just travel around

00:50:44.020 --> 00:50:49.740
with me and I hired some kids
and stuff, essentially to help

00:50:49.740 --> 00:50:51.900
with language barrier, because
I thought it was important.

00:50:51.900 --> 00:50:55.520
And I've done that a little bit
in other places, but most

00:50:55.520 --> 00:50:57.250
the time completely
on your own.

00:50:57.250 --> 00:50:58.490
You have to figure
it out as you go.

00:50:58.490 --> 00:50:59.740
It's crazy.

00:51:02.008 --> 00:51:03.700
Do you all like travel?

00:51:03.700 --> 00:51:04.060
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:04.525
ROBERT REID: Oh, OK.

00:51:04.525 --> 00:51:06.850
That's good.

00:51:06.850 --> 00:51:08.450
Most people do, I think.

00:51:08.450 --> 00:51:08.923
Yes?

00:51:08.923 --> 00:51:12.240
AUDIENCE: Any tips about
being a travel writer?

00:51:12.240 --> 00:51:13.720
ROBERT REID: To be
a travel writer?

00:51:13.720 --> 00:51:14.170
Yeah.

00:51:14.170 --> 00:51:16.900
Well, it's kind of the best
time, in some ways.

00:51:16.900 --> 00:51:17.810
Kind of the best and worst.

00:51:17.810 --> 00:51:20.610
There's never been more travel
writers, because of

00:51:20.610 --> 00:51:21.550
self-publishing.

00:51:21.550 --> 00:51:23.220
I mean, people create blogs.

00:51:23.220 --> 00:51:25.590
And that's the way to start.

00:51:25.590 --> 00:51:26.690
It used to be you had
to get clips.

00:51:26.690 --> 00:51:27.530
You had to have something.

00:51:27.530 --> 00:51:30.270
I got into Lonely Planet,
because I'd written for a

00:51:30.270 --> 00:51:32.590
newspaper in Vietnam, an
English language paper.

00:51:32.590 --> 00:51:33.870
And so I said here's clips.

00:51:33.870 --> 00:51:34.640
I can write.

00:51:34.640 --> 00:51:35.280
Look at this.

00:51:35.280 --> 00:51:37.170
And now you can publish
yourself, so it's

00:51:37.170 --> 00:51:38.060
easier to get in.

00:51:38.060 --> 00:51:39.840
And then some people are
blogging, and they create

00:51:39.840 --> 00:51:41.000
their little niche--

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:45.080
plastic stool, street eats,
or something like this.

00:51:45.080 --> 00:51:47.530
Very niche kind of things that
you have to eat on a plastic

00:51:47.530 --> 00:51:48.590
stool and talk about that.

00:51:48.590 --> 00:51:49.290
Whatever it is.

00:51:49.290 --> 00:51:50.906
I'm just making stuff up.

00:51:50.906 --> 00:51:55.280
But if you develop your niche
and persona, without worrying

00:51:55.280 --> 00:51:58.850
about money initially, through
the blog, then things happen.

00:51:58.850 --> 00:52:01.870
And it's funny, for better or
worse, we're at a time, when

00:52:01.870 --> 00:52:04.360
writers are increasingly doing
things connecting with

00:52:04.360 --> 00:52:05.360
marketing and PR.

00:52:05.360 --> 00:52:07.390
And they're getting sponsorship
deals with Expedia

00:52:07.390 --> 00:52:07.780
and things like--

00:52:07.780 --> 00:52:09.695
I don't know if I'm allowed
to say Expedia here.

00:52:09.695 --> 00:52:11.170
Are you allowed to say that?

00:52:11.170 --> 00:52:12.160
I don't even know.

00:52:12.160 --> 00:52:13.610
With Bing?

00:52:13.610 --> 00:52:14.810
No, I'm just joking.

00:52:14.810 --> 00:52:20.380
And so people are finding more
unique ways of doing it than

00:52:20.380 --> 00:52:22.080
just the old newspaper way.

00:52:22.080 --> 00:52:24.975
You could argue there's a
downside to that too.

00:52:24.975 --> 00:52:26.370
But more people are writing.

00:52:26.370 --> 00:52:29.650
And a lot of people want
to be travel writers.

00:52:29.650 --> 00:52:31.220
There isn't a lot of money.

00:52:31.220 --> 00:52:34.410
Rock stars, music stars,
movie stars, they all--

00:52:34.410 --> 00:52:35.800
you know who they are.

00:52:35.800 --> 00:52:36.630
Famous travel writers?

00:52:36.630 --> 00:52:38.050
You probably don't
know how to name.

00:52:38.050 --> 00:52:39.990
I mean, there isn't a lot of
fame, and there's isn't a lot

00:52:39.990 --> 00:52:42.390
of money in it, but
you get to travel.

00:52:42.390 --> 00:52:45.620
But I think that I would
start writing first.

00:52:45.620 --> 00:52:48.010
Guidebooks used to be a very
easy way to get in.

00:52:48.010 --> 00:52:49.220
It's a lot harder now.

00:52:49.220 --> 00:52:51.185
Lonely Planet isn't looking for
authors right now because

00:52:51.185 --> 00:52:52.710
they have so many already.

00:52:52.710 --> 00:52:54.990
And so that changes, but
they look for people

00:52:54.990 --> 00:52:56.700
with a local expertise.

00:52:56.700 --> 00:52:59.620
I mean if you know Delaware
better than anyone in the

00:52:59.620 --> 00:53:05.040
world, you could be the Queen
of Delaware and govern all

00:53:05.040 --> 00:53:06.220
Delaware travel content.

00:53:06.220 --> 00:53:08.055
Because they want to find
someone that really knows it.

00:53:08.055 --> 00:53:10.390
It's not the best example,
but I'd like

00:53:10.390 --> 00:53:11.650
to know about Delaware.

00:53:11.650 --> 00:53:12.715
Can you tell me about
Delaware?

00:53:12.715 --> 00:53:13.467
Do you know?

00:53:13.467 --> 00:53:14.717
Oh, OK.

00:53:16.670 --> 00:53:21.460
Any other questions
about anything?

00:53:21.460 --> 00:53:23.825
Well, thank you very much.

00:53:23.825 --> 00:53:25.973
I hope that was fun.

00:53:32.110 --> 00:53:33.360
Work hard this afternoon.

